Time series analysis (from statistical point-of-view). Some of the steps are useful for understanding the time series data, before one applies ML predictive models on the data.

The data used here is about airline passengers, which can be downloaded from: https://github.com/jbrownlee/Datasets/blob/master/airline-passengers.csv If you use R, you can load the data directly. https://stat.ethz.ch/R-manual/R-devel/library/datasets/html/AirPassengers.html

Before doing further analysis, one should check if the time series is stationary or not.

A stationary time series is a time series whose statistical properties like mean, variance, autocorrelation are constant over time.

It is easier to work with a stationary time series, compared to with a non-stationary one. Therefore When doing time series analysis, one tries to transform the data to make the data stationary by: 1) identifying and removing trends 2) identifying and removing seasonal effects 3) identifying and removing both trends and seasonal effects at the same time by taking time-difference (calculating the difference in values between time steps).

From the figure above, one can see that the trend is "increasing", and that there is some seasonality. Therefore, this time series is non-stationary.

To check if a univariate (one variable) time series is stationary or not, one can use a statistical test called Dickey-fuller Test.

The null hypothesis: the time series is non-stationary (i.e., the observations are time dependent).

If the "Test statistic" gives value less than "Critical value(s)", we can reject the null hypothesis.

Before we do the Dickey-Fuller Test, we should try to establish the so-called rolling statistics (mean and std of certain window of interest (X samples) and slide this window along until end of samples is reach. 1) For any time t, the mean is calculated as the mean of the last 12 months 2) For any time t, the std is calculated as the std of the last 12 months If mean and std of a time series from the rolling statistics are not flat over time, then this suggest that the time series is not stationary.

In [8]:
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller
def test_stationarity(timeseries):
    
    #Determing rolling statistics
    rolmean = timeseries.rolling(window=12).mean()
    rolstd = timeseries.rolling(window=12).std()
    
    #Plot rolling statistics
    plt.plot(timeseries, color='blue',label='Original')
    plt.plot(rolmean, color='red', label='Rolling Mean')
    plt.plot(rolstd, color='black', label = 'Rolling Std')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.title('Rolling Mean & Standard Deviation')
    plt.show()
    
    #Perform Dickey-Fuller test:
    print('Results of Dickey-Fuller Test:')
    dftest = adfuller(timeseries, autolag='AIC')
    dfoutput = pd.Series(dftest[0:4], index=['Test Statistic','p-value','#Lags Used','Number of Observations Used'])
    for key,value in dftest[4].items():
        dfoutput['Critical Value (%s)'%key] = value
    print(dfoutput)

The Test Statistic value is higher than any of the critical values therefore we fail to reject the null hypothesis that the time series is non-stationary.

One can then transform the time series, model the trend and seasonality, and remove these trend and seasonality to make the time series stationary. One can apply log, sq-rt, or cube root function to transform the time series.

With the p-values, we can say that we are almost 99% confident that the series is now a stationary.

Instead of just removing the trend, we can try to remove both trend and seasonality by differencing. This means that we calculate the difference between the value at a particular time with that of the previous time.

The Time series is now stationary. We can now make predictive models on the time series using differencing, and then transform back the add the trend and seasonality back into the predicted values to get the predicted values in the original form.

We can now use statistical modelling method called ARIMA to make predictive models that can be used to make prediction/forecast.

Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average (ARIMA) uses 3 parameters (p,d,q). p is the number of Auto-Regressive terms (AR order). If p is 3 the predictor for y(t) will be y(t-1),y(t-3). q is the number of Moving-Average terms (MA order). If p is 3 the predictor for y(t) will be y(t-1),y(t-2), y(t-3). d is the number of differences or the number of non-seasonal differences (differencing order).

To get q, we can use Autocorrelation Function (ACF). It measures the correlation between the observation at the current point in time and the observations at all previous points in time.

To get p, we can use Partial Autocorrelation Function (PACF). It is used to measure the correlation between observations made at two points in time, i.e., between y(t) and y(t-p).

https://www.statsmodels.org/stable/generated/statsmodels.tsa.stattools.acf.html#statsmodels.tsa.stattools.acf https://www.statsmodels.org/stable/generated/statsmodels.tsa.stattools.pacf.html?highlight=pacf

In [21]:
from statsmodels.tsa.arima_model import ARIMA
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import acf, pacf

lag_acf = acf(ts_log_diff, nlags=20)
lag_pacf = pacf(ts_log_diff, nlags=20, method='ols')
#ols=ordinary least square

#Plot ACF to get p
plt.subplot(121)
plt.plot(lag_acf)
plt.axhline(y=0,linestyle='--',color='gray')
plt.axhline(y=-1.96/np.sqrt(len(ts_log_diff)),linestyle='--',color='gray')
plt.axhline(y=1.96/np.sqrt(len(ts_log_diff)),linestyle='--',color='gray')
plt.title('Autocorrelation Function')

#Plot PACF to get q
plt.subplot(122)
plt.plot(lag_pacf)
plt.axhline(y=0,linestyle='--',color='gray')
plt.axhline(y=-1.96/np.sqrt(len(ts_log_diff)),linestyle='--',color='gray')
plt.axhline(y=1.96/np.sqrt(len(ts_log_diff)),linestyle='--',color='gray')
plt.title('Partial Autocorrelation Function')
plt.tight_layout()
